    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Connection Pooling and Backpressure for GenAI"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every I/O call your GenAI API makes \u2014 to Anthropic, to Postgres, to Redis \u2014 involves a network connection. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Connection pooling",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " keeps a set of reusable connections open rather than opening and closing one per request (which costs 5\u2013100ms per TCP+TLS handshake). "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Backpressure",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the mechanism that says \"no more work until the pool has capacity\" \u2014 preventing connection exhaustion and cascading overload."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Connection pools for Anthropic API, Postgres, and Redis with backpressure mechanisms",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "httpx Connection Pool for Anthropic Calls"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The AsyncAnthropic client uses "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "httpx.AsyncClient",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " internally, which maintains a connection pool. Configure it at startup and reuse the client for the lifetime of the application:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import httpx\nfrom anthropic import AsyncAnthropic\nfrom contextlib import asynccontextmanager\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\n\n_anthropic_client: AsyncAnthropic | None = None\n\n@asynccontextmanager\nasync def lifespan(app: FastAPI):\n    global _anthropic_client\n    _anthropic_client = AsyncAnthropic(\n        http_client=httpx.AsyncClient(\n            limits=httpx.Limits(\n                max_connections=100,       # pool size (open sockets)\n                max_keepalive_connections=20,  # idle keepalive connections\n                keepalive_expiry=30,       # close idle connections after 30s\n            ),\n            timeout=httpx.Timeout(\n                connect=5.0,\n                read=120.0,   # streaming can take a while\n                write=10.0,\n                pool=30.0,    # wait up to 30s for a pool slot\n            ),\n        )\n    )\n    yield\n    await _anthropic_client._client.aclose()  # flush and close all connections\n\napp = FastAPI(lifespan=lifespan)\n\ndef get_anthropic() -> AsyncAnthropic:\n    return _anthropic_client\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Not Create a New Client per Request?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# WRONG \u2014 creates a new TCP+TLS connection on every request\nasync def bad_handler(prompt: str) -> str:\n    client = AsyncAnthropic()   # new pool each time\n    resp = await client.messages.create(...)\n    # pool teardown at GC \u2014 TLS handshake cost: ~200ms per request\n    return resp.content[0].text\n\n# CORRECT \u2014 reuses the shared pool\nasync def good_handler(prompt: str, client: AsyncAnthropic = Depends(get_anthropic)) -> str:\n    resp = await client.messages.create(...)   # pool reuse: ~0ms overhead\n    return resp.content[0].text\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncpg Pool for Postgres"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncpg.create_pool",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for async Postgres access. It maintains a pool of persistent connections, handles reconnect, and supports connection-level statement caching:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncpg\nfrom contextlib import asynccontextmanager\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\n\n_pg_pool: asyncpg.Pool | None = None\n\n@asynccontextmanager\nasync def lifespan(app: FastAPI):\n    global _pg_pool\n    _pg_pool = await asyncpg.create_pool(\n        dsn=\"postgresql://user:pass@localhost:5432/genai\",\n        min_size=5,                       # always-open connections\n        max_size=20,                      # cap on open connections\n        max_inactive_connection_lifetime=300,  # close idle conns after 5 min\n        statement_cache_size=100,         # cache prepared statements per connection\n        command_timeout=30,               # cancel queries that take > 30s\n    )\n    yield\n    await _pg_pool.close()\n\nasync def fetch_user(user_id: str) -> dict | None:\n    async with _pg_pool.acquire() as conn:\n        # acquire() blocks if all max_size connections are in use\n        row = await conn.fetchrow(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1\", user_id)\n        return dict(row) if row else None\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PgBouncer for High-Connection Environments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Postgres has a hard "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "max_connections",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (typically 100\u2013200). With multiple uvicorn workers each holding a pool of 20 connections, you can hit this limit. PgBouncer acts as a connection multiplexer between your app pools and Postgres:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# PgBouncer config (pgbouncer.ini) for transaction pooling\n# [databases]\n# genai = host=127.0.0.1 port=5432 dbname=genai\n#\n# [pgbouncer]\n# listen_port = 6432\n# pool_mode = transaction      # return connection to pool after each transaction\n# max_client_conn = 1000       # app-side connections (many \u2192 PgBouncer)\n# default_pool_size = 20       # PgBouncer \u2192 Postgres connections\n\n# App connects to PgBouncer, not Postgres directly:\n_pg_pool = await asyncpg.create_pool(\n    dsn=\"postgresql://user:pass@localhost:6432/genai\",  # PgBouncer port\n    min_size=2,\n    max_size=10,  # PgBouncer handles multiplexing\n)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "aioredis Connection Pool"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "aioredis (redis-py async) manages a connection pool automatically when you call "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from_url",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Tune the pool size to match your concurrency:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import redis.asyncio as aioredis\n\n# Module-level pool \u2014 created once\nredis_pool: aioredis.Redis | None = None\n\nasync def init_redis():\n    global redis_pool\n    redis_pool = aioredis.from_url(\n        \"redis://localhost:6379/0\",\n        decode_responses=True,\n        max_connections=50,           # pool cap\n        socket_timeout=5,             # read timeout\n        socket_connect_timeout=2,     # connect timeout\n        retry_on_timeout=True,\n    )\n\nasync def get_redis() -> aioredis.Redis:\n    return redis_pool\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Backpressure Mechanisms"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "1. asyncio.Semaphore (In-Process)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest backpressure gate: limit concurrent in-flight LLM calls within one process."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom anthropic import AsyncAnthropic\n\n_llm_sem = asyncio.Semaphore(15)  # at most 15 concurrent LLM calls per worker\n\nasync def call_llm(prompt: str) -> str:\n    async with _llm_sem:\n        # All coroutines beyond 15 block here \u2014 event loop is still available\n        # for other work while waiting\n        resp = await get_anthropic().messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\n            max_tokens=512,\n            messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}],\n        )\n    return resp.content[0].text\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "2. Request Queue with Bounded Size"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reject new requests with 503 when the queue is full \u2014 better than making users wait indefinitely:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\n\n_request_queue: asyncio.Queue = asyncio.Queue(maxsize=200)\n\nasync def enqueue_llm_call(prompt: str) -> str:\n    try:\n        future: asyncio.Future = asyncio.get_event_loop().create_future()\n        _request_queue.put_nowait((prompt, future))\n    except asyncio.QueueFull:\n        raise HTTPException(503, \"Server busy \u2014 retry shortly\")\n    return await future  # wait for the result\n\nasync def queue_consumer():\n    \"\"\"Background consumer \u2014 processes one item at a time from the queue.\"\"\"\n    while True:\n        prompt, future = await _request_queue.get()\n        try:\n            result = await call_llm(prompt)\n            future.set_result(result)\n        except Exception as exc:\n            future.set_exception(exc)\n        finally:\n            _request_queue.task_done()\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "3. Backpressure Headers on 429"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the semaphore or queue is full, return 429 with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Retry-After",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " so clients know when to retry rather than hammering the server:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from fastapi import Request, Response\nfrom fastapi.responses import JSONResponse\n\nasync def maybe_rate_limit(request: Request, call_next):\n    \"\"\"Middleware: check semaphore headroom before processing.\"\"\"\n    sem_value = _llm_sem._value   # remaining permits (not thread-safe but indicative)\n    if sem_value == 0:\n        return JSONResponse(\n            status_code=503,\n            content={\"error\": \"server_busy\", \"retry_after\": 5},\n            headers={\"Retry-After\": \"5\"},\n        )\n    return await call_next(request)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
