        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Monitoring Connection Pool Health"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# asyncpg pool metrics\npool_info = {\n    \"size\":       _pg_pool.get_size(),         # current open connections\n    \"min_size\":   _pg_pool.get_min_size(),\n    \"max_size\":   _pg_pool.get_max_size(),\n    \"idle\":       _pg_pool.get_idle_size(),    # connections not in use\n    \"free_slots\": _pg_pool.get_max_size() - _pg_pool.get_size(),\n}\n\n# Expose as Prometheus gauges via prometheus-client\nfrom prometheus_client import Gauge\n\npg_pool_idle = Gauge(\"pg_pool_idle_connections\", \"Idle asyncpg connections\")\npg_pool_used = Gauge(\"pg_pool_used_connections\", \"In-use asyncpg connections\")\n\nasync def update_pool_metrics():\n    idle = _pg_pool.get_idle_size()\n    used = _pg_pool.get_size() - idle\n    pg_pool_idle.set(idle)\n    pg_pool_used.set(used)\n\n# Schedule update_pool_metrics() every 15s via Celery Beat or an asyncio task\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Pitfalls"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Connection leak: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "acquiring a pool connection in an asyncpg context manager then raising before the context exits leaks the connection slot. Always use 'async with pool.acquire() as conn:'.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pool too small under load: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "if pool max_size < concurrent requests, coroutines queue up waiting for a slot. Monitor 'idle connections' \u2014 if it hits zero under load, increase max_size.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pool too large: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "each Postgres connection uses ~5\u201310MB of server RAM. 200 connections \u00d7 8MB = 1.6GB of Postgres RAM consumed by connections alone. Size to what Postgres can serve.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Timeout on pool.acquire(): "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "asyncpg raises asyncpg.TooManyConnectionsError when max_size is hit. Catch it and return 503 rather than letting the error propagate as a 500.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Using blocking redis-py in an async context: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "import redis (sync) inside a FastAPI handler blocks the event loop for the duration of the Redis call. Always use redis.asyncio.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing Connection Pool Behaviour"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Test that your application handles pool exhaustion gracefully without leaking connections or hanging indefinitely:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nimport pytest\nimport asyncpg\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_pool_exhaustion_returns_503():\n    \"\"\"Verify the API returns 503 when all pool slots are held.\"\"\"\n    from httpx import AsyncClient\n    from app.main import app\n\n    # Simulate pool exhaustion: hold all connections\n    hold_tasks = []\n    async def hold_connection():\n        async with _pg_pool.acquire() as conn:\n            await asyncio.sleep(5)  # hold for 5s\n\n    # Exhaust the pool (max_size=2 in test config)\n    for _ in range(2):\n        hold_tasks.append(asyncio.create_task(hold_connection()))\n    await asyncio.sleep(0.1)  # let tasks acquire connections\n\n    async with AsyncClient(app=app, base_url=\"http://test\") as client:\n        resp = await client.post(\"/v1/chat/completions\", json={\"prompt\": \"hello\"})\n\n    assert resp.status_code == 503\n    assert \"retry_after\" in resp.json()\n\n    for t in hold_tasks:\n        t.cancel()\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_connection_released_on_exception():\n    \"\"\"Verify pool connection is released even when an exception occurs.\"\"\"\n    initial_idle = _pg_pool.get_idle_size()\n\n    async def faulty_query():\n        async with _pg_pool.acquire() as conn:\n            raise ValueError(\"intentional error\")\n\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError):\n        await faulty_query()\n\n    # Pool should return to same idle count \u2014 no leak\n    assert _pg_pool.get_idle_size() == initial_idle\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adaptive Pool Sizing with Health Checks"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In Kubernetes, when pods scale up or down, the connection count changes dynamically. A health-check endpoint can expose pool state for readiness probes:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from fastapi import APIRouter\n\nrouter = APIRouter()\n\n@router.get(\"/health/ready\")\nasync def readiness():\n    \"\"\"\n    Kubernetes readiness probe.\n    Fails if Postgres or Redis are unreachable, or if pools are exhausted.\n    \"\"\"\n    checks = {}\n\n    # Check Postgres pool\n    try:\n        async with _pg_pool.acquire(timeout=2) as conn:\n            await conn.fetchval(\"SELECT 1\")\n        checks[\"postgres\"] = \"ok\"\n    except Exception as exc:\n        checks[\"postgres\"] = str(exc)\n\n    # Check Redis\n    try:\n        await redis_pool.ping()\n        checks[\"redis\"] = \"ok\"\n    except Exception as exc:\n        checks[\"redis\"] = str(exc)\n\n    # Check pool headroom\n    pg_headroom = _pg_pool.get_max_size() - _pg_pool.get_size()\n    checks[\"pg_pool_free_slots\"] = pg_headroom\n\n    all_ok = all(v == \"ok\" for k, v in checks.items() if k != \"pg_pool_free_slots\")\n    return {\"status\": \"ready\" if all_ok else \"degraded\", \"checks\": checks}\n\n@router.get(\"/health/live\")\nasync def liveness():\n    \"\"\"Kubernetes liveness probe \u2014 just verify the process is alive.\"\"\"\n    return {\"status\": \"alive\"}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Connection pooling is free performance: done right, it eliminates repeated TLS handshake overhead and keeps your app responsive under load. Pair it with bounded semaphores and 503/429 responses as backpressure valves \u2014 never let the connection pool become an unbounded buffer that silently delays every request."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}